      <title>#192 - A Conversation with Paul Bloom</title>
      <pubDate>Tue, 17 Mar 2020 22:04:55 -0400</pubDate>
      <guid isPermaLink="false">1570295</guid>
      <link>https://samharris.org/subscriber-extras/192-march-17-2020/</link>
      <itunes:subtitle/>
      <description><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">In this episode of the podcast, Sam Harris and Paul Bloom speak about the psychology of adapting to the coronavirus pandemic, the disastrous analogy between coronavirus and flu, the political siloing of information, true and false concerns over "panic," pressuring China to close down their live animal markets, the economic implications and possible silver linings of the pandemic, what our response suggests about our ability to deal with climate change, Biden vs Sanders, the ethics of praising one's enemies, and other topics.</span>

<b>Paul Bloom</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is the Brooks and Suzanne Ragen Professor of Psychology at Yale University. His research explores how children and adults understand the physical and social world, with special focus on morality, religion, fiction, and art.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Website: </span><a href="http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/</span></a>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Twitter: </span><a href="https://twitter.com/paulbloomatyale" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">@paulbloomatyale</span></a>]]></description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<span style="font-weight: 400;">In this episode of the podcast, Sam Harris and Paul Bloom speak about the psychology of adapting to the coronavirus pandemic, the disastrous analogy between coronavirus and flu, the political siloing of information, true and false concerns over "panic," pressuring China to close down their live animal markets, the economic implications and possible silver linings of the pandemic, what our response suggests about our ability to deal with climate change, Biden vs Sanders, the ethics of praising one's enemies, and other topics.</span>

<b>Paul Bloom</b><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is the Brooks and Suzanne Ragen Professor of Psychology at Yale University. His research explores how children and adults understand the physical and social world, with special focus on morality, religion, fiction, and art.</span>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Website: </span><a href="http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">http://campuspress.yale.edu/paulbloom/</span></a>

<span style="font-weight: 400;">Twitter: </span><a href="https://twitter.com/paulbloomatyale" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer"><span style="font-weight: 400;">@paulbloomatyale</span></a>]]></content:encoded>
